@bgedik I don't think @jeking3  was talking about the maven plugin. From what I understand people can write their own generators and use it to generate their code.

I'm not too sure about how it works but I didn't make any changes to `t_generator` base class since it was already using `ostream` parameters.
Though I changed some function signatures to use `ostream` instead of `ofstream` in `t_oop_generator` and others.

In that case, this will break binary compatibility. Because, in C++, changing the type of a function parameter in a shared library API will require a recompilation of the dependent applications. Here is a good list of do's and don'ts for binary compatibility: https://community.kde.org/Policies/Binary_Compatibility_Issues_With_C%2B%2B

It says 'changing any of the types of the arguments in the parameter list, including changing the const/volatile qualifiers of the existing parameters (instead, add a new method)' is among the things that break binary compatibility.

@jeking3 If this is really a concern,  there is a simple solution to it. In ``t_oop_generator`` we can keep the old versions as additional overload, forwarding them to the new versions. You' are in a better position to judge. My thinking is that it is better to document this in the release notes only.

@nsuke, my use-case is to process a thrift message that was received complete and not chunked, similarly to how ruby or java implementations are done.
To get that done, as you noticed, I cut down the `loop` function to become a single message processor. `timeout` and multiplexing make little sense in this context given that the IO is done by someone else (I am picturing standard req/resp via HTTP, or a async queue of thrift instructions via RabbitMQ)
I tried to imagine sharing code path with `loop` but I can't see it. What did you have in mind?
Not being some erlang master I tried to keep this patch safe by not modifying any existing code, only adding a function that exists in other libraries.

@jeking3, the patch is ready as is

```
root@31d4b8941d65:/thrift/src# git diff HEAD
diff --git a/test/perl/TestServer.pl b/test/perl/TestServer.pl
index 7f76060a..7257241e 100644
--- a/test/perl/TestServer.pl
+++ b/test/perl/TestServer.pl
@@ -99,8 +99,8 @@ if ($opts{ssl} and not defined $opts{cert}) {
     exit 1;
 }

-my $handler    = ThriftTest::ThriftTestHandler->new();
-my $handler2   = ThriftTest::SecondServiceHandler->new();
+my $handler    = ThriftTestHandler->new();
+my $handler2   = SecondServiceHandler->new();
 my $processor  = ThriftTest::ThriftTestProcessor->new($handler);
 my $processor2 = ThriftTest::SecondServiceProcessor->new($handler2);
```

@vanjabucic as we're modifying generic interface, I don't think it's good idea to make an assumption for the underlying transport (that someone else does the IO without propagating errors, unlike existing transports).
Multiplex is about handling multiple services in one wire, so relevence doesn't seem to be different for `loop` and `process`.
Looking at it, sticking to error handler and returning `ok` would be really strange interface.

@nsuke I am open to suggestions. We should make it the best way we can. Take a look at ruby or java interface for ideas.
(note: passing {:err, v} || {:ok, v} tuples is common practice in some languages)

Ruby Code (from http_server example):
```ruby
@processor = in_processor
@protocol_factory = in_protocol_factory
transport = IOStreamTransport.new(request.body, **out**)
protocol = @protocol_factory.get_protocol(transport)
@processor.process(protocol, protocol) # <----
```
They are using IOStreamTransport to directly modify http response IO object. Can't do things like that in FP style, we need to return something.
Any ideas?
